      Betterment
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CAny one may so arrange his affairs that his taxes shall be as low =
as possible,=E2=80=9D  said Learned Hand; =E2=80=9Che is not bound to choos=
e that pattern which will best pay the Treasury; there is not even a patrio=
tic duty to increase one=E2=80=99s taxes.=E2=80=9D But what about the rever=
se? If you are an investment adviser with a=C2=A0fiduciary duty to your cli=
ents, do you have an obligation to minimize their taxes? You do have a duty=
 to be loyal and diligent and do a good job for them; you try to maximize t=
heir risk-adjusted return, and generally speaking reducing taxes increases =
returns more=C2=A0reliably=C2=A0than does, like, having a lot of investment=
 skill. =E2=80=9CI will buy stocks that go up, so my clients have high retu=
rns=E2=80=9D: hard to do. =E2=80=9CI will sell stocks that have gone down a=
nd rotate into similar stocks to generate losses to shield my clients=E2=80=
=99 capital gains=E2=80=9D: pretty straightforward as these things go.
On the other hand, if you fail=C2=A0to minimize your clients=E2=80=99 taxes=
, it would be a little weird for a government regulator to come in and puni=
sh you. It=E2=80=99s not clear that government regulators have, you know, a=
n interest in encouraging tax minimization? But here is=C2=A0a  US Securiti=
es and Exchange Commission enforcement action fining Betterment LLC $9 mill=
ion for not fulfilling its fiduciary duty to minimize its customers=E2=80=
=99 taxes. Well, technically the fine is for=C2=A0advertising=C2=A0that it =
did a better job of minimizing taxes than it actually did:
The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that, from 2016 to 2019, Betterment, in commu=
nicating with clients, misstated or omitted several material facts concerni=
ng [tax loss harvesting], a service that scans clients=E2=80=99 accounts fo=
r opportunities to reduce their tax burden. According to the order, at diff=
erent times, Betterment failed to disclose a change in the software related=
 to its scanning frequency, failed to disclose a programming constraint aff=
ecting certain clients, and had two computer coding errors that prevented T=
LH from harvesting losses for some clients. Collectively, these issues adve=
rsely impacted more than 25,000 client accounts, resulting in those clients=
 losing approximately $4 million in potential tax benefits.
For instance, for a while Betterment told clients that it  scanned their po=
rtfolios every day for tax-loss-harvesting opportunities, but in fact it wa=
s only scanning them every=C2=A0other=C2=A0day. Eventually it fixed this pr=
oblem and went back to scanning them every day, but in the meantime =E2=80=
=9Capproximately 25,000 clients lost approximately $1.9 million in potentia=
l tax benefits as a result of the undisclosed change in scanning frequency.=
=E2=80=9D The US government got $1.9 million more in revenue because Better=
ment was not checking every client=E2=80=99s portfolio every day to minimiz=
e taxes. Which was bad I guess.
We   talked a while back about a  ProPublica investigation into tax-loss ha=
rvesting that big banks like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. do on behalf of their=
 ultra-high-net-worth=C2=A0clients. ProPublica confronted Goldman with its =
findings and Goldman basically said, oh, right, a few of these trades were =
probably too aggressive, but for the most part (in ProPublica=E2=80=99s wor=
ds) =E2=80=9Cthe bank will continue its broader practice of finding similar=
 stocks that achieve the same effect.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIt would be irrespo=
nsible not to,=E2=80=9D I wrote: Goldman is a fiduciary, its customers are =
paying it for tax optimization, so it does the best job it can do of optimi=
zing their taxes. One could object, on public-spiritedness grounds, but tha=
t really is the job. And if you don=E2=80=99t do it diligently, you will ge=
t in trouble.

