I just want to put it out there that a really interesting=C2=A0securities f=
raud lawsuit against Bed Bath & Beyond Inc.=C2=A0is, like, two weeks away. =
  Bloomberg News reports:

Bed Bath & Beyond Inc.=C2=A0is once again laying the groundwork for a bankr=
uptcy filing as its last-ditch efforts to raise cash come up short.=C2=A0
The retailer is holding talks with advisers and lenders ahead of a Chapter =
11 filing that could come in the next few weeks, according to people with k=
nowledge of the conversations, who asked not to be named discussing private=
 plans. Bed Bath & Beyond is also looking at financing options to help fund=
 itself during bankruptcy, the people added.=C2=A0
The filing could come before an April 26 deadline by which the company=C2=
=A0sought=C2=A0to raise another $300 million from equity investors, the peo=
ple said, adding that a decision isn=E2=80=99t final and plans could change=
.=C2=A0
Bed Bath & Beyond has shocked investors before: earlier this year, the comp=
any=C2=A0staved off=C2=A0a bankruptcy filing after raising $360 million fro=
m a hedge fund investor that bought shares at a discount. ...
Even as the retailer prepares for bankruptcy, shares staged another rally i=
n a move reminiscent of meme-stock mania two years ago, where wild swings i=
n stocks became commonplace. Bed Bath & Beyond spiked 41% in the first 40 m=
inutes of trading on Wednesday, bringing the stock price to nearly 49 cents=
, more than double its closing price last week.

Bed Bath & Beyond has been   pounding out tens of millions of dollars of st=
ock to retail investors in at-the-market stock offerings   as all this has =
been going on; for all I know it has been selling stock into=C2=A0today=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0rally. Why not? In all of its public disclosure, Bed Bath has =
been reasonably clear about the risks that investors face, with the main on=
e being that the company is probably going to go bankrupt with no recovery =
for the equity. =E2=80=9CWe expect that we will likely file for bankruptcy =
protection notwithstanding the sale of common stock pursuant to the Purchas=
e Agreement,=E2=80=9D  Bed Bath said in the risk factors to its stock offer=
ing prospectus last week. And now the stock has gone=C2=A0up=C2=A0today on =
reports that=C2=A0bankruptcy is closer.
Somebody is buying Bed Bath stock today at $0.46,=C2=A0possibly from the co=
mpany itself,
  [1]
 and if that stock becomes worthless in a week because of a bankruptcy fili=
ng that person is going to sue. Though of course the stock will probably ra=
lly even more if the company actually files. (Will the company keep selling=
 stock after it files?   Hertz tried it!)
On the one hand: If you are a company, you have some fiduciary obligations =
to your shareholders, and it seems like poor form to sell them stock moment=
s before you file for bankruptcy and render the stock worthless. They will =
definitely be mad at you, and=C2=A0they will definitely be able to make som=
e argument of the form =E2=80=9Cyou knew more about the risks than you told=
 us, and you tricked us into buying stock.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C  Everything i=
s securities fraud,=E2=80=9D I often say; every bad thing that happens to a=
 company can also be characterized as securities fraud. Going bankrupt is b=
ad, so there you go.
On the other hand: You absolutely did not trick=C2=A0them. They tricked the=
mselves, if anything, though you took advantage of their self-deception. US=
 securities law is basically founded on full=C2=A0disclosure, and if you=C2=
=A0say =E2=80=9Chey here=E2=80=99s some stock but FYI we=E2=80=99re about t=
o go bankrupt,=E2=80=9D then arguably you have done all that the law requir=
es of you. (Also saying that might make people=C2=A0more=C2=A0likely to buy=
 the stock? People love a dare.) Also if you are a company and you are mome=
nts away from bankruptcy, arguably your fiduciary obligations are to your=
=C2=A0creditors, not your shareholders, so going out and raising more money=
 from shareholders so that you can immediately hand it over to creditors=C2=
=A0is exactly=C2=A0what you are supposed to be doing.

 =20
   =20
      Duration
   =20
 =20

Bank runs are largely a self-reinforcing phenomenon: If people worry about =
a bank, they will take their money out, which will lead to the bank not hav=
ing enough money, which will make more people worry and take their money ou=
t, etc.
But the recent set of   bank runs in the US were caused largely by regional=
 banks=E2=80=99 unrealized losses on their long-term bond portfolios as int=
erest rates rose: The banks borrowed short-term from depositors to invest l=
ong-term in safe bonds, and as interest rates went up those bonds lost valu=
e, leaving the banks undercapitalized and causing depositors to flee. That =
is a partially self-reinforcing phenomenon: If your depositors are all flee=
ing, you have to sell bonds to get cash to give to the depositors, further =
driving down the bonds=E2=80=99 prices. (And the Fed stepped in to break th=
is cycle in part by   promising to=C2=A0lend=C2=A0money against those bonds=
, so they don=E2=80=99t have to be sold.)=C2=A0
But it is also a partially self-limiting phenomenon, because if rising inte=
rest rates cause a banking crisis, then the banking crisis will cause (long=
-term expectations of) interest rates to fall, so  your bonds will go back =
up again:

Rising rates over the past year saddled banks with losses on their massive =
portfolios of bonds. Those losses helped sink Silicon Valley Bank last mont=
h. But since that failure sparked turmoil across the banking sector, fallin=
g bond yields have narrowed those losses.
Bank of America Corp., which released its first-quarter earnings Tuesday, i=
s the latest to benefit. The bank is still deeply underwater on its bonds t=
hat it is holding to maturity, but unrealized losses shrank by $9.5 billion=
 from three months ago and $17.1 billion from six months ago, when rates we=
re peaking. =E2=80=A6
After the banking turmoil began, bond yields dropped sharply. Between March=
 9, the day before SVB failed, and the end of the quarter, the yield on the=
 10-year Treasury note fell 0.43 percentage point to 3.49%. It edged up to =
3.59% on Monday.
That yield, which is the benchmark for many types of bonds stowed in banks=
=E2=80=99 securities portfolios, has been falling largely because the banki=
ng turmoil heightened fears of a recession.
In turn, unrealized losses have been shrinking.=C2=A0

If rising interest rates cause banks to fail, that will lead to a recession=
, which will cause interest rates to drop, which will rescue those banks. T=
he trick is the timing.
Elsewhere in banks and interest-rate risk:

Few U.S. banks protected themselves against rising interest rates during th=
e Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s monetary-tightening campaign last year, accordi=
ng to a research paper that says unhedged securities holdings are more wide=
spread than investors might realize.
The paper=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CLimited Hedging and Gambling for Resurrection by=
 U.S. Banks During the 2022 Monetary Tightening?=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94contends =
that hundreds of other banks share that risk, which played a role in the co=
llapse last month of Silicon Valley Bank. The paper didn=E2=80=99t single o=
ut individual institutions, instead presenting an analysis of aggregate dat=
a.

Here is the paper, by Erica Jiang, Gregor Matvos, Tomasz Piskorski and Amit=
 Seru:
We analyze the extent to which U.S. banks hedged their asset exposure as th=
e monetary policy tightened in 2022. We use call reports data for interest =
rate swaps covering close to 95% of all bank assets and supplement it with =
hand-collected data on broader hedging activity from 10K and 10Q filings fo=
r all publicly traded banks (68% of all bank assets). Interest rate swap us=
e is concentrated among larger banks who hedge a small amount of their asse=
ts. Over three quarters of all reporting banks report no material use of in=
terest rate swaps. Swap users represent about three quarters of all bank as=
sets, but on average hedge only 4% of their assets and about one quarter of=
 their securities. Only 6% of aggregate assets in the U.S. banking system a=
re hedged by interest rate swaps. We also find limited hedging of interest =
rate exposure by publicly traded banks and by banks which report the durati=
on of their assets. The use of hedging and other interest rate derivatives =
was not large enough to offset a significant share of the $2.2 trillion los=
s in the value of U.S. banks=E2=80=99 assets (Jiang et al. 2023). The durat=
ion of bank assets increased during 2022, exposing banks to additional inte=
rest rate risk. We find slightly less hedging for banks whose assets were m=
ost exposed to interest rate risk. Banks with the most fragile funding =E2=
=80=93 i.e., those with highest uninsured leverage -- sold or reduced their=
 hedges during the monetary tightening. This allowed them to record account=
ing profits but exposed them to further rate increases. These actions are r=
eminiscent of classic gambling for resurrection: if interest rates had decr=
eased, equity would have reaped the profits, but if rates increased, then d=
ebtors and the FDIC would absorb the losses.
There was a lot of this discussion when SVB failed =E2=80=94=C2=A0a lot of =
people asking =E2=80=9Cwhy didn=E2=80=99t they just hedge their interest-ra=
te risk?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 and honestly I find it a bit strange. Banks are=
   in some deep sense=C2=A0in the business of maturity transformation; thei=
r whole function is to borrow short-term from depositors (who can=C2=A0take=
 their money back any time, but mostly don=E2=80=99t) and=C2=A0invest long-=
term in loans and bonds. The way they get paid for doing that business, mos=
t of the time, is through the yield curve
  [2]
: Short-term interest rates are usually lower than long-term rates, so a ba=
nk that borrows short to lend long makes money from the difference in rates=
. And then if rates suddenly go up a lot (and invert, so that short-term=C2=
=A0deposit rates are=C2=A0higher=C2=A0than long-term bond rates) the banks=
=C2=A0lose=C2=A0a ton of money, whoops.
I guess they should have hedged, but broadly speaking if you were a bank in=
 2020 and you were taking deposits at 0% and investing them in Treasuries a=
nd then swapping the Treasuries to floating, you weren=E2=80=99t earning an=
y money: You were paying 0% on deposits, earning like 0.6% on your Treasuri=
es, and then giving up most of that yield on the swap.
  [3]
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CBorrow short to lend long and then swap all your long-term a=
ssets back to short-term rates=E2=80=9D is economically the same as =E2=80=
=9Cborrow short to lend short,=E2=80=9D which is not really a core banking =
business model because it doesn=E2=80=99t make money, certainly not enough =
money to pay for branches and tellers.
  [4]
=C2=A0The banking business model is inherently risky, and hedging it so tha=
t it is no longer risky also makes it no longer a business model.

 =20
   =20
      Gensler vs. crypto
   =20
 =20

US Securities and Exchange Commission Chair Gary Gensler  testified at a he=
aring of the House Financial Services hearing=C2=A0yesterday=C2=A0about cry=
pto regulation. We have   talked a   lot   about SEC   regulation of crypto=
 recently, and I want to point out three things about his testimony.
First of all,   my general view of crypto regulation in 2023 has been that =
Gensler and the SEC want to crack down on crypto, and the financial crisis =
in=C2=A0crypto last year =E2=80=94=C2=A0especially the failure of=C2=A0FTX =
Trading Ltd., whose   now-indicted leaders gave a lot of money to politicia=
ns to try to shape crypto regulation=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0has given them the=
 political cover to do so. In 2021, people in crypto would say that the SEC=
=E2=80=99s posture was stifling innovation, and they=E2=80=99d get a sympat=
hetic hearing in Congress and the press; in 2023, we have more data on how =
that innovation turned out, and there is less sympathy.=C2=A0
But yesterday=E2=80=99s hearing=C2=A0undermines my view. There=C2=A0are=C2=
=A0members of Congress who seem to think that crypto is valuable and innova=
tive, that the SEC is stifling innovation, etc., all the stuff that was sta=
ndard in 2021=C2=A0and that retreated=C2=A0after the high-profile crypto fr=
auds and failures in 2022. Ahead of the hearing, all the Republicans on the=
 committee  sent Gensler a letter =E2=80=9Cslamming the Commission=E2=80=99=
s approach to digital asset regulation and attempts to force digital asset =
trading platforms to =E2=80=98come in and register=E2=80=99 under the ill-f=
itting national securities exchange (NSE) framework.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CTo d=
ate,=E2=80=9D they write,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe SEC has forced digital asset ma=
rket participants into regulatory frameworks that are neither compatible wi=
th the underlying technology nor applicable because the firms=E2=80=99 acti=
vities do not involve an offering of securities.=E2=80=9D
This is   the crypto industry view, that (1) most crypto tokens are not sec=
urities and (2) even if they are securities, the SEC should adapt its rules=
 to make it more feasible to register crypto tokens (and crypto exchanges),=
 because it is   basically impossible to register tokens under existing sec=
urities rules. I assumed that, after FTX, most politicians would not want t=
o loudly endorse=C2=A0that view, but apparently I am wrong. Seems relativel=
y bullish =E2=80=94=C2=A0more bullish than I thought, anyway =E2=80=94 for =
crypto,=C2=A0and for crypto exchanges.
Second, Gensler  was asked if Ethereum is a security, and he declined to an=
swer directly. I have mentioned this problem before; basically:
=09It seems widely accepted in the US regulatory world that Ethereum is tre=
ated as a commodity, not a security: It is regulated by the Commodity Futur=
es Trading Commission,  Ether futures trade on commodities exchanges, it ca=
n be sold without securities registration, etc.=09This seems to be largely =
a historical accident, a grandfathering-in of Ethereum because it got too b=
ig and too popular before the SEC paid attention to it, and there=E2=80=99s=
 a pretty good argument that if most crypto tokens are securities (because =
they raised money from investors to fund work by a centralized team on a pr=
oject that promised to make the investors rich), then so is Ethereum.
  [5]

=09Gensler=C2=A0surely=C2=A0thinks it=E2=80=99s a security =E2=80=94=C2=A0h=
ow could he not, he thinks every crypto is a security =E2=80=94=C2=A0but he=
 can=E2=80=99t come out and say that because it would contradict the accept=
ed view. =E2=80=9COne pet theory of mine,=E2=80=9D   I wrote last month,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cis that if you hung out with SEC Chair Gary Gensler and got a f=
ew drinks into him, he would tell you =E2=80=98obviously Ethereum is a secu=
rity.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

Anyway I previously thought all of that due to Gensler=E2=80=99s, like, bod=
y language, but now we have him saying it =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, rather, declin=
ing to say it =E2=80=94 before Congress.
Third, there was pushback against Gensler for not owning or=C2=A0using=C2=
=A0crypto. =E2=80=9CIt is hard to understand something without using it,=E2=
=80=9D  writes Anthony Pompliano. =E2=80=9CThe idea that we have regulators=
 who are actively making rules for something that they have never used seem=
s confusing.=E2=80=9D
This seems like a simple mistake. Nobody asks the administrator of the Drug=
 Enforcement Administration if she has ever used meth. =E2=80=9CHow can you=
 regulate meth if you have never used meth=E2=80=9D is a non sequitur. =E2=
=80=9CHow can you understand meth if you have never used meth,=E2=80=9D sim=
ilarly, has easy answers: You can look at=C2=A0the science and sociology of=
 how it affects people, decide that it=E2=80=99s bad, and regulate it accor=
dingly.=C2=A0
If you start from the assumption that crypto is the future of payments, or =
of the financial system, or of art or identity or the web or whatever, then=
, sure, the people regulating it should understand its mechanics and possib=
ly be users and enthusiasts themselves. If you don=E2=80=99t start from tha=
t assumption, though, it seems reasonable to let the regulators examine the=
=C2=A0effects=C2=A0of crypto and decide whether it=E2=80=99s good or bad. I=
 think it is plausible for a regulator to look at crypto=E2=80=99s track re=
cord in 2022 and say =E2=80=9Cwe need much more restrictive anti-fraud enfo=
rcement in crypto=E2=80=9D without using crypto himself, or understanding t=
he technical workings of a blockchain, or whatever. He can judge by the eff=
ects. Nobody would say to the prosecutors looking into the FTX bankruptcy, =
=E2=80=9Chow can you prosecute this case if you never even owned any   FTT =
tokens?=E2=80=9D Owning   FTT tokens is not a prerequisite to understanding=
 or prosecuting FTX. Arguably owning FTT tokens is proof that you=C2=A0didn=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0understand FTX.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      T-Swift vs. FTX
   =20
 =20

I do feel like if I were an enormously wealthy celebrity =E2=80=94=C2=A0lik=
e, Tom Brady- or Taylor Swift-level celebrity =E2=80=94=C2=A0and someone ca=
me to me with a large bag of money and said =E2=80=9Chi we will give you th=
is bag of money=C2=A0in exchange for recording a brief message endorsing ou=
r company,=E2=80=9D I would probably ask questions like =E2=80=9Cis your co=
mpany doing crime?=E2=80=9D I am not saying that every celebrity should hav=
e a detailed due diligence checklist and ask penetrating legal or business =
questions of every company that they endorse. But if I am saying that if yo=
u are an enormously wealthy celebrity, (1) you have a lot of money, so one =
more bag of money doesn=E2=80=99t matter=C2=A0that=C2=A0much and (2) your r=
eputation is very valuable, so lending your credibility to a crime is very =
expensive for you. Anyway  good for Taylor Swift:

Taylor Swift was one of the only celebrities who did their due diligence on=
 crypto exchange FTX, according to the lawyer suing the now-bankrupt compan=
y=E2=80=99s celebrity promoters.
Attorney Adam Moskowitz has gone after basketball legend Shaquille O=E2=80=
=99Neal, football star Tom Brady, =E2=80=9CSeinfeld=E2=80=9D creator Larry =
David and more than a dozen other FTX promoters in a class action lawsuit t=
hat accuses them of promoting the sale of unregistered securities.=C2=A0
Moskowitz is seeking $5 billion in the lawsuit, he said during an episode o=
f The Scoop podcast with Frank Chaparro. He claims the exchange=E2=80=99s c=
elebrity boosters didn=E2=80=99t do their due diligence to check whether th=
ey may be breaking the law before cutting TV and digital ads for FTX.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe one person I found that did that was Taylor Swift. In our disc=
overy, Taylor Swift actually asked them, 'Can you can you tell me that thes=
e are not unregistered securities?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Moskowitz said. Swift =
reportedly came close to inking a $100 million sponsorship deal with FTX, b=
ut the partnership never materialized. Swift did not immediately respond to=
 a request for comment.

I will say that, among FTX=E2=80=99s problems, =E2=80=9Cselling unregistere=
d securities=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t rank very high. Did FTX sell unregist=
ered securities? Oh=C2=A0probably,
  [6]
=C2=A0but no one has bothered to come after it for that,
  [7]
=C2=A0what with the   bigger problem of FTX   going bankrupt because billio=
ns of dollars of customer money   was missing. Taylor Swift did not exactly=
 ask FTX the=C2=A0correct=C2=A0due diligence questions. And there are some =
frauds=C2=A0that are designed to be robust to the=C2=A0obvious due=C2=A0dil=
igence questions, to trap superficially sophisticated investors, to reassur=
e you that they are not doing the illegal thing that you think they=E2=80=
=99re doing, and to misdirect you from the fact that they are doing a diffe=
rent illegal thing.
On the other hand there are lots of other frauds where they ask you for mon=
ey, and you ask them if they are doing a particular crime,=C2=A0and they sa=
y =E2=80=9Ceep, gotta go!=E2=80=9D even though they are in fact doing some =
entirely different crime. If you are doing a fraud, it=E2=80=99s probably e=
asier not to deal with people who have any sort of suspicions, even the wro=
ng ones. If you ask a crypto exchange =E2=80=9Care you selling unregistered=
 securities=E2=80=9D and they say =E2=80=9Coh no, we would never do that, h=
ere is a legal opinion from a reputable firm,=E2=80=9D that doesn=E2=80=99t=
 mean that you are safe; they might be doing other crimes instead. But if y=
ou ask them that and they say =E2=80=9Cmumble mumble look over there=E2=80=
=9D and run away,=C2=A0then you dodged a bullet.

