  [1] No,  technically, from its broker/investment banker, B. Riley Princip=
al Capital II LLC, who is buying the stock to sell it into the market, and =
who will presumably also be named in the lawsuit.=20


  [2] And through credit spreads, though that too can be hedged, and if ban=
ks had huge credit losses people would complain that they should have hedge=
d more. The stylized model of a modern US bank is less =E2=80=9Cthe bank ta=
kes deposits, makes mortgages, and earns a spread for taking the credit ris=
k of the mortgages=E2=80=9D and more =E2=80=9Cthe bank takes deposits, make=
s mortgages, sells the credit risk to Fannie Mae or Freddie Mac and earns m=
oney for taking the duration risk of the mortgages.=E2=80=9D


  [3] For some pretty fake numbers: The 10-year Treasury yielded about 0.63=
% in April 2020, the Secured Overnight Financing Rate was in the neighborho=
od of 0.02% to 0.03%, and Bloomberg tells me (USOSFR10 Curncy GP) that 10-y=
ear SOFR swaps were trading at about 0.4%. So you=E2=80=99d be earning abou=
t 0.25%.


  [4] Arguably =E2=80=9Cborrow short to lend short=E2=80=9D is the business=
 model of a money-market fund, which does not have branches or tellers or c=
apital requirements, so it can live on a few basis points of income.


  [5] Another possible issue here is that   originally Ethereum was proof-o=
f-work, but last year it switched to being proof-of-stake. It seems clear t=
hat proof-of-stake blockchains, which pay =E2=80=9Cdividends=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9Cinterest=E2=80=9D of tokens to holders of tokens who lock them up =
to validate transactions, are *more* security-like than proof-of-work block=
chains; I don=E2=80=99t think the difference is absolute, but there=E2=80=
=99s a difference. =E2=80=9CEthereum was not a security when it launched, b=
ut is now because now it=E2=80=99s PoS=E2=80=9D is a coherent position, tho=
ugh I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s right. I think Ethereum was a securi=
ty when it launched, because it raised money in an offering that obviously =
met the Howey test, and it is not a security now because that ship has sail=
ed and everyone kind of agreed not to treat it like a security.


  [6] FTX is a largely offshore exchange that sold crypto assets mostly to =
non-US persons, making them mostly exempt from  US registration requirement=
s. But it did have a US exchange that sold crypto assets to US persons, and=
 presumably all of its, like, Super Bowl advertising was targeted at US per=
sons. Were some FTX-listed crypto assets securities?   My view is that   th=
e SEC=E2=80=99s view is that virtually all crypto assets are securities, an=
d virtually all US crypto exchanges are breaking the law by operating unreg=
istered securities exchanges, so if FTX hadn=E2=80=99t imploded and lost it=
s customers=E2=80=99 money the SEC would eventually have gotten around to s=
uing FTX for offering unregistered securities. But, again, not the biggest =
problem!


  [7] In particular, the SEC *has*   brought an enforcement action against =
FTX, but for defrauding its equity investors, not for offering unregistered=
 securities. This doesn=E2=80=99t mean that the SEC concedes the point that=
 all of its token listings were not securities, just that it=E2=80=99s not =
top of mind for anyone.


