<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Betterment</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAny one may so arrange his affairs th=
at his taxes shall be as low as possible,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31219425.261443/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm=
5lbGwuZWR1L3N1cGN0L2h0bWwvOTItMTk0MS5aQy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb26=
1f133" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> said Learned Hand</a>; =E2=80=9Che is not bound to choose t=
hat pattern which will best pay the Treasury; there is not even a patriotic=
 duty to increase one=E2=80=99s taxes.=E2=80=9D But what about the reverse?=
 If you are an investment adviser with a=C2=A0fiduciary duty to your client=
s, do you have an obligation to <em>minimize</em> their taxes? You do have =
a duty to be loyal and diligent and do a good job for them; you try to maxi=
mize their risk-adjusted return, and generally speaking reducing taxes incr=
eases returns more=C2=A0<em>reliably</em>=C2=A0than does, like, having a lo=
t of investment skill. =E2=80=9CI will buy stocks that go up, so my clients=
 have high returns=E2=80=9D: hard to do. =E2=80=9CI will sell stocks that h=
ave gone down and rotate into similar stocks to generate losses to shield m=
y clients=E2=80=99 capital gains=E2=80=9D: pretty straightforward as these =
things go.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you <em>fail=C2=A0</em>t=
o minimize your clients=E2=80=99 taxes, it would be a little weird for a go=
vernment regulator to come in and punish you. It=E2=80=99s not clear that g=
overnment regulators have, you know, an interest in encouraging tax minimiz=
ation? But here is=C2=A0a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/31219425.261443/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2U=
vMjAyMy04MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd59e6d25" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> US Securities and E=
xchange Commission enforcement action</a> fining Betterment LLC $9 million =
for not fulfilling its fiduciary duty to minimize its customers=E2=80=99 ta=
xes. Well, technically the fine is for=C2=A0<em>advertising=C2=A0</em>that =
it did a better job of minimizing taxes than it actually did:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that=
, from 2016 to 2019, Betterment, in communicating with clients, misstated o=
r omitted several material facts concerning [<em>tax loss harvesting</em>],=
 a service that scans clients=E2=80=99 accounts for opportunities to reduce=
 their tax burden. According to the order, at different times, Betterment f=
ailed to disclose a change in the software related to its scanning frequenc=
y, failed to disclose a programming constraint affecting certain clients, a=
nd had two computer coding errors that prevented TLH from harvesting losses=
 for some clients. Collectively, these issues adversely impacted more than =
25,000 client accounts, resulting in those clients losing approximately $4 =
million in potential tax benefits.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance, for a while Betterment told clie=
nts that it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/312194=
25.261443/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvaWEtNjI4O=
C5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1a4f158e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> scanned their portfolio=
s every day</a> for tax-loss-harvesting opportunities, but in fact it was o=
nly scanning them every=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>day. Eventually it fixed t=
his problem and went back to scanning them every day, but in the meantime =
=E2=80=9Capproximately 25,000 clients lost approximately $1.9 million in po=
tential tax benefits as a result of the undisclosed change in scanning freq=
uency.=E2=80=9D The US government got $1.9 million more in revenue because =
Betterment was not checking every client=E2=80=99s portfolio every day to m=
inimize taxes. Which was bad I guess.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31219425.261443/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDkvYWRhbmktaGFzLWFuLWluZGV4LXByb2JsZW0_Y21waWQ9QkJE=
MDQxOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXI=
mdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB661cddbb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  talked a while back</a> about a <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31219425.261443/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvc=
HVibGljYS5vcmcvYXJ0aWNsZS9pcnMtZmlsZXMtdGF4ZXMtd2FzaC1zYWxlcy1nb2xkbWFuLXNh=
Y2hz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb01b51c8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ProPublica investigation</=
a> into tax-loss harvesting that big banks like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. do=
 on behalf of their ultra-high-net-worth=C2=A0clients. ProPublica confronte=
d Goldman with its findings and Goldman basically said, oh, right, a few of=
 these trades were probably too aggressive, but for the most part (in ProPu=
blica=E2=80=99s words) =E2=80=9Cthe bank will continue its broader practice=
 of finding similar stocks that achieve the same effect.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
It would be irresponsible not to,=E2=80=9D I wrote: Goldman is a fiduciary,=
 its customers are paying it for tax optimization, so it does the best job =
it can do of optimizing their taxes. One could object, on public-spiritedne=
ss grounds, but that really is the job. And if you don=E2=80=99t do it dili=
gently, you will get in trouble.</p>
